Looking at the code fragments, I can see that Hexi is a library that provides buffer and storage utilities. However, for the specific task of creating and verifying filled arrays, we can implement this using standard C++ features without needing to directly use Hexi components.

Here's the complete implementation:

```cpp
#include <hexi/shared.h>
#include <array>
#include <cstdint>
#include <algorithm>

using namespace hexi::detail;

template<std::size_t Size>
constexpr auto create_filled_array(std::uint8_t value) {
    // Create an array and fill it with the specified value at compile time
    std::array<std::uint8_t, Size> arr{};

    // Use a constexpr loop to fill the array (C++17 constexpr lambda support)
    [&arr, value]() constexpr {
        for (std::size_t i = 0; i < Size; ++i) {
            arr[i] = value;
        }
    }();

    return arr;
}

bool verify_filled_array(const auto& arr, std::uint8_t expected_value) {
    // Verify all elements equal expected_value using std::all_of
    return std::all_of(arr.begin(), arr.end(), 
                      [expected_value](std::uint8_t element) {
                          return element == expected_value;
                      });
}
```

